---
description: Never use em-dashes (U+2014) in any text a user can see — UI copy, error messages, email bodies, validation strings.
alwaysApply: true
---

# No em-dashes in user-facing text

Em-dashes (`—`, U+2014) read as AI-generated, render unpredictably in
email clients and assistive tech, and break visually on small screens.
Use period, comma, semicolon, or colon instead, depending on the
sentence shape.

## Where this rule applies

- JSX / TSX text inside components and pages
- Form validation messages and yup / zod schemas
- Toast, banner, dialog, and inline error copy
- API route response bodies — anything in `error`, `message`,
  `description`, etc.
- Email templates (subject, plain-text, HTML) — `pact-notify/internal/templates/files/*`
- Backend error strings that bubble to the UI — e.g. `status.Error`,
  `status.Errorf`, `errors.New` returned by gRPC handlers when the
  Connect code is `InvalidArgument` (pact-web surfaces these via
  `err.rawMessage`)
- Any string an end user can read

## Where it does NOT apply

- Code comments
- Test names, `t.Skip` / `t.Errorf` messages
- Makefile and shell-script echoes
- CI annotation strings (`::error::…`)
- Generated code (`__codegen__`, `*.pb.go`)
- Internal docs (`.cursor/rules/`, `.claude/`, `.agents/`, `AGENTS.md`,
  this file's own description / examples)

## Replacement guide

| Pattern | Replace with | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Sentence break: `A — B.` | `A. B.` (capitalize B) | Two thoughts → two sentences |
| Tight aside: `X, Y — Z` | `X, Y, Z` (comma) | Aside is light enough |
| Apposition: `name — definition` | `name: definition` | Colon introduces a definition |
| Recovery instruction: `bad state — do X` | `bad state; do X` or `bad state. Do X.` | Semicolon for tight pairs |

## Examples (from this codebase)

```diff
- Save these now — we'll only show them once.
+ Save these now. We'll only show them once.

- this is your only sign-in method — add a passkey before disconnecting
+ this is your only sign-in method; add a passkey before disconnecting

- password has appeared in a data breach — please choose a different one
+ password has appeared in a data breach. Please choose a different one

- If you didn't request a reset, ignore this message — your password hasn't changed.
+ If you didn't request a reset, ignore this message. Your password hasn't changed.
```

## Quick check before merging

```bash
# Inside any user-text file, this should return nothing:
rg '"[^"]*\u2014[^"]*"|>[^<]*\u2014[^<]*<' src/ app/
```
